Apah and i̱pah both mean ‘eat’, but are used differently. Apah takes a direct object: it’s used for eating bread, a food, something that’s mentioned or implied. I̱pah refers to the general act of eating or having a meal: a specific food isn’t mentioned or implied. Apah has special forms for marking persons: apalih ‘I am eating it’, ishpah ‘you are eating it’, apah ‘he/she is eating it’, ípah ‘we are eating it’, hashpah ‘you all are eating it’. The same is true in the negative: akpoh 'I haven't eaten it', etc.

Apah and i̱pah both mean ‘eat’, but are used differently. Apah takes a direct object: it’s used for eating bread, a food, something that’s mentioned or implied. I̱pah refers to the general act of eating or having a meal: a specific food isn’t mentioned or implied. Apah has special forms for marking persons: apalih ‘I am eating it’, ishpah ‘you are eating it’, apah ‘he/she is eating it’, ípah ‘we are eating it’, hashpah ‘you all are eating it’. The same is true in the negative: akpoh 'I haven't eaten it', etc.
